The general rules are simple. I suppose these can be used for fitness criteria also. Parts should be placed as close as possible and the traces should be as short as possible. Typical configuration options allow for single or double side traces. Jumpers allowed or not (would count against fitness per jumper), allow through-holes, and designation of reserves areas. There are often many other options but these can be discussed some other time.  

I would assume the CPPN would be given a schematic along with PCB parameters (and options). It would have to then start to place the parts then route the traces. Fitness would be determined, CPPN would then evolve and try again. 

My knowledge in CPPNs is weak but growing as I read these messages and other materials online. But this sounds like a good use. I suppose it is similar to the traveling salesman problem. 

Sent from my iPhone

